WEBVTT

00:01.901 --> 00:03.470
     - If this job is what      
       you want, great.         

00:03.536 --> 00:05.338
       But if you're just       
       running, don't go.       

00:05.405 --> 00:06.840
 Maybe you're not aware of it,  

00:06.906 --> 00:09.209
   but she did everything she   
could to save you from yourself.

00:09.275 --> 00:11.544
    You should be her friend    
       or leave her alone.      

00:12.579 --> 00:14.047
   - Do you remember me, sir?   

00:14.114 --> 00:15.715
     - You made my dinner.      

00:15.782 --> 00:17.650
        (truck honking)         
          - Look out!           

00:17.717 --> 00:20.053
          (crashing)            
       (Bashir coughing)        

00:20.120 --> 00:21.621
             - Sir!             

00:21.688 --> 00:23.656
     - I really hated you       
    the first night we met.     

00:23.723 --> 00:26.426
     You were so confident      
      in your instincts.        

00:26.493 --> 00:28.328
         I was jealous.         

00:28.395 --> 00:30.764
       I had never trusted      
        myself like that.       

00:30.830 --> 00:32.399
       - She's in V-tach.       

00:32.465 --> 00:33.433
       (monitors beeping)       

00:33.500 --> 00:35.635
         (tense music)          

00:35.702 --> 00:37.237
           - Clear.             

00:43.543 --> 00:46.379
          (soft music)          

00:54.721 --> 00:56.423
     - The scars will fade.     

00:59.025 --> 01:00.960
        (truck honking)         

01:01.027 --> 01:02.695
           (crashing)           

01:02.762 --> 01:04.364
       (glass shattering)       

01:04.431 --> 01:08.101
        (sirens wailing)        

01:13.306 --> 01:15.475
      - Uh, just remind me      
       of your name again?      

01:15.542 --> 01:16.543
       - Uh, Bashir Hamed.      

01:16.609 --> 01:18.645
    Thank you for seeing me,    
           Dr. Bishop.          

01:18.711 --> 01:21.081
   - Did we meet in the first   
   round of March interviews?   

01:21.147 --> 01:24.084
  - No, I wasn't, uh, applying  
     for one at that stage.     

01:24.150 --> 01:25.218
        - Why was that?         

01:25.285 --> 01:27.587
      - I was hoping to get     
    a position as a surgeon.    

01:27.654 --> 01:29.089
- You mean a surgical residency.

01:29.155 --> 01:31.224
  - No, I've already completed  
     my surgical residency.     

01:31.291 --> 01:33.359
     Did they not give you      
        my background?          

01:33.426 --> 01:34.894
     - So when you didn't       
    get hired as a surgeon,     

01:34.961 --> 01:36.996
you thought you would fall back 
    on emergency medicine?      

01:37.063 --> 01:39.265
  - No, I was a field surgeon,  

01:39.332 --> 01:41.868
        and emergency has       
    an overlapping skillset.    

01:41.935 --> 01:43.403
        - Yes, it does.         

01:44.437 --> 01:46.606
  Right, you were the one that  
  didn't provide your records,  

01:46.673 --> 01:48.241
your medical school transcripts?

01:48.308 --> 01:50.977
  - Yeah, there's a political   
   situation in my country.     

01:51.044 --> 01:53.079
   - Yeah. So, what have you    
          been doing            

01:53.146 --> 01:54.414
        while you've been       
       looking for a job?       

01:54.481 --> 01:56.449
      Any volunteer hours,      
         research work?         

01:56.516 --> 01:57.951
      - Just got the call.      

01:58.017 --> 01:59.853
   Jackknifed tractor-trailer   
         on the Gardner.        

01:59.919 --> 02:02.355
      Two cars went over        
   the guardrail and they're    
    all heading to us, Jed.     

02:02.422 --> 02:04.023
      - Alright. Page every     
     resident on the floor.     

02:04.090 --> 02:06.559
  Make sure teams from vascular 
 and neurology are standing by. 

02:06.626 --> 02:08.061
     Prime the blood bank.      

02:08.128 --> 02:10.396
      - And I will clear        
    the backlog at imaging.     

02:11.264 --> 02:15.268
        - To be honest,         
     our residency program      
  is already over-subscribed.   

02:15.335 --> 02:18.471
        - I once clamped        
     a man's femoral artery     
       with binder clips.       

02:18.538 --> 02:21.608
  We didn't have proper tools,  
        but he survived.        

02:21.674 --> 02:23.710
      - Huh... Lucky, huh?      

02:23.776 --> 02:26.379
 Look, all the best, Dr. Hamed. 

02:35.321 --> 02:38.324
     Alright, first arrival     
       is two minutes out.      

02:38.391 --> 02:40.293
One is hemodynamically unstable,

02:40.360 --> 02:41.995
         they've been           
     transfusing en route.      

02:42.061 --> 02:44.164
       The second sounds        
     like a crushed femur,      

02:44.230 --> 02:46.099
      so I wanna make sure      
      we're communicating.      

02:46.166 --> 02:48.401
   Every second counts, okay?   

02:48.468 --> 02:51.037
      (indistinct chatter)      

03:23.770 --> 03:25.438
        (Bashir exhales)        

03:29.409 --> 03:31.311
         (line ringing)         

03:31.377 --> 03:33.213
 (phone ringing and vibrating)  

03:34.614 --> 03:36.382
             - Hey.             
          - Hey, uh...          

03:36.449 --> 03:38.318
 I need to tell you something.  

03:38.384 --> 03:40.220
  It's going to be difficult.   

03:40.286 --> 03:41.454
             Um...              

03:41.955 --> 03:43.790
       Are you somewhere        
         we can talk?           

03:43.856 --> 03:45.758
      - Yeah... What's up?      

03:53.166 --> 03:56.069
        (opening theme)         

04:14.287 --> 04:16.155
     (high-pitched ringing)     

04:18.057 --> 04:19.592
- I need to know what happened! 

04:19.659 --> 04:21.661
 Why do you keep running away?  
         Who are you?           

04:21.728 --> 04:24.030
        (truck honking)         
          (crashing)            

04:24.097 --> 04:25.832
       - The restaurant         
       is a crime scene.        

04:25.898 --> 04:27.567
   What were you doing there?   
         (locker slams)         

04:33.072 --> 04:35.074
      (Theo clears throat)      
             - Hey.             

04:36.743 --> 04:39.612
    - I keep trying to find     
      ways to tell Amira,       

04:39.679 --> 04:41.648
       but she'll be sad        
     and worried in London      

04:41.714 --> 04:43.116
  and maybe want to come home.  

04:43.182 --> 04:45.418
     Am I wrong to give it      
       a few more days?         

04:45.985 --> 04:47.287
       - Not at all, man.       

04:48.755 --> 04:50.189
       You sleeping, yet?       

04:52.158 --> 04:54.260
    What else are you, um...    

04:55.728 --> 04:56.829
          ...feeling?           

04:56.896 --> 04:59.032
         - Um... Numb.          

05:00.700 --> 05:04.504
   Afraid of what will happen   
          when I'm not.         

05:04.570 --> 05:09.008
        - Look, I booked        
    our flights to Montreal,    
      so tomorrow, we'll...     

05:10.943 --> 05:12.645
 The funeral's the first step.  

05:12.712 --> 05:14.781
 - The family said they wanted  
       to keep it small,        

05:14.847 --> 05:16.816
       so should I even...      

05:16.883 --> 05:18.484
I mean, do I belong there or...?

05:18.551 --> 05:21.054
     - You loved her, Bash.     
        Of course you do.       

05:26.993 --> 05:31.097
   Hey, uh, can we talk about   
       Bash still working?      

05:31.164 --> 05:32.732
        - Theo, really?         
 What do you expect him to do?  

05:32.799 --> 05:34.400
   Sit at home, just to like,   
        stare at a wall?        

05:34.467 --> 05:36.235
   Besides, you're here, too.   
         - But for him.         

05:36.302 --> 05:38.471
      I wanna support him.      

05:38.538 --> 05:41.140
  Hey, have you, uh, have you   
   bought your flight, yet?     

05:41.207 --> 05:44.911
    - Uh, no... I haven't...    
          (baby crying)         

05:49.048 --> 05:51.517
       - Does anyone know       
       whose baby this is?      

05:53.119 --> 05:55.188
         (baby cooing)          
            - Hey.              

05:58.891 --> 06:01.494
  - How are you doing, Bashir?  
           - I'm okay.          

06:01.561 --> 06:03.229
  - I wanted to check in again  

06:03.296 --> 06:07.033
  because with your residency   
     ending, technically,       
      you owe us nothing.       

06:07.100 --> 06:09.669
        I appreciate you        
       offering to cover,       

06:09.736 --> 06:11.504
but if being here is too much...

06:11.571 --> 06:14.440
 - She'd be upset if her shifts 
        weren't covered.        

06:15.141 --> 06:18.211
 - I know I've said it already, 
       but I am so sorry.       

06:18.277 --> 06:19.746
       We're all just...        

06:19.812 --> 06:21.681
    Whatever you need, okay?    

06:22.782 --> 06:23.816
             Uh...              

06:23.883 --> 06:26.319
     - Um, we found her out     
      in the waiting room.      

06:26.386 --> 06:29.655
 There's no sign of a parent.   
 I'd say five, six months old.  

06:29.722 --> 06:31.557
        - Is she sick?          
  - Now, I did a quick check.   

06:31.624 --> 06:33.192
  Temp's good, colour's good,   
       but I would like         

06:33.259 --> 06:35.561
  to do a more thorough exam.   
      - What's this now?        

06:35.628 --> 06:38.498
     - Rhoda, do you know       
  if anyone's missing a baby?   

06:38.564 --> 06:40.700
       - Maybe the parents      
    are here somewhere sick?    

06:40.767 --> 06:43.269
 - Well... I will do the exam.  

06:43.336 --> 06:44.937
         (baby cooing)          

06:45.004 --> 06:47.006
- How does a baby get abandoned 

06:47.073 --> 06:49.709
      in a busy hospital        
   without anybody noticing?    

06:50.309 --> 06:51.844
      - Chronic hepatitis.      

06:51.911 --> 06:54.680
   Patient's anxious because    
    he tried texting Mags.      

06:54.747 --> 06:57.083
       She did that kind        
        of thing a lot.         

06:57.650 --> 06:58.918
     - Okay. I'll cover it.     

06:58.985 --> 07:00.253
         Thanks, Rhoda.         
             - Yeah.            

07:00.319 --> 07:02.522
         (baby cooing)          
            - Yeah.             

07:02.588 --> 07:04.957
    What are you doing here     
       all by yourself?         

07:05.024 --> 07:08.461
- I hear pedes is hiring in case
   Cleveland doesn't work out.  

07:08.528 --> 07:10.096
          Who's this?           

07:10.663 --> 07:12.298
   - An anonymous baby girl.    

07:12.365 --> 07:14.100
  Someone just left her here.   

07:15.067 --> 07:17.270
   I don't know why. Or how.    

07:17.336 --> 07:19.872
     - Listen, I can cover      
      Trauma OR tomorrow.       

07:19.939 --> 07:22.975
    I heard it's the service.   
  - Oh, no need. I'll be here.  

07:25.111 --> 07:26.879
           - June...            
           (sighing)            

07:26.946 --> 07:29.615
       I was there the day      
        your father died.       

07:29.682 --> 07:31.951
    You couldn't even admit     
         it happened.           

07:32.018 --> 07:34.387
     - Uh, this needs to be     
        heated up, right?       

07:34.454 --> 07:36.122
    When they're this small.    

07:36.656 --> 07:39.725
 - Ten seconds in the microwave 
      if my memory serves.      

07:39.792 --> 07:41.093
     - We'll get that done.     

07:41.160 --> 07:42.829
       - You don't need         
    to do that again, June.     

07:42.895 --> 07:44.430
  - That was different, okay?   

07:44.497 --> 07:46.432
           My father,           
   he did everything he could   

07:46.499 --> 07:48.367
   to make me feel unwanted.    

07:48.434 --> 07:51.604
    And, like, hate myself.     

07:52.839 --> 07:55.475
         - But it wasn't        
      like that with Mags.      

07:55.541 --> 07:56.876
             Right?             

07:58.144 --> 08:00.413
         You need to let        
       yourself feel this.      

08:00.480 --> 08:01.681
     - You must be hungry.      

08:01.747 --> 08:03.683
        Warm this while         
       I check her over?        

08:09.355 --> 08:11.057
          I heard you.          

08:13.326 --> 08:14.660
             I did.             

08:18.498 --> 08:20.199
             - Hey.             

08:20.266 --> 08:21.868
             - Hey.             

08:24.003 --> 08:25.271
             Um...              

08:25.972 --> 08:27.940
     The lady in E has been     
        waiting a while.        

08:28.007 --> 08:30.576
         Do you mind?           
         - Yeah, sure.          

08:36.482 --> 08:38.117
    Daphne? I'm Dr. Hunter.     

08:38.184 --> 08:39.719
  - I've been timing you guys.  

08:39.785 --> 08:44.123
 420 minutes at three agonizing 
      hip spasms per hour.      

08:44.190 --> 08:46.392
 That's one every 900 seconds,  
         give or take.          

08:46.459 --> 08:47.827
    - That's some fast math.    

08:47.894 --> 08:49.795
    - Necessary when you run    
       your own business.       

08:49.862 --> 08:52.465
   - Well, I'm told you have    
     rheumatoid arthritis.      

08:52.532 --> 08:55.268
       And you were in for      
    the same pain yesterday?    

08:55.334 --> 08:56.903
        - Which I realize       
       is a cardinal sin,       

08:56.969 --> 08:58.538
    but they said come back     
       if it got worse.         

08:58.604 --> 09:00.306
 I'm warm, fatigued, nauseous,  

09:00.373 --> 09:02.508
  and those are warning signs   
  I'm not supposed to ignore.   

09:02.575 --> 09:04.410
    - For septic arthritis.     
    But your temp is good,      

09:04.477 --> 09:06.979
    and yesterday's X-rays      
 didn't raise any alarm bells.  

09:07.046 --> 09:09.382
   So why don't you lie back    
     on the gurney for me.      

09:10.149 --> 09:13.452
So I'm gonna feel both sides of 
 your hips for swelling, okay?  

09:15.521 --> 09:16.822
           (exhales)            

09:16.889 --> 09:18.824
   And what kind of business    
          do you run?           

09:18.891 --> 09:20.560
       - I'm a sex worker.      

09:21.627 --> 09:24.130
   People always either react   
       to the line of work      

09:24.196 --> 09:25.965
   or to the fact that I look   
       like an accountant.      

09:26.032 --> 09:27.400
        (Theo chuckles)         
   - I think it's definitely    

09:27.466 --> 09:29.468
     the accountant thing.      
    - Obviously, seizing up     

09:29.535 --> 09:31.504
       with crippling pain      
   is not great for business.   

09:31.571 --> 09:33.239
           (sighing)            
    - Why don't you sit up?     

09:33.306 --> 09:35.741
     Um, do you have a GP?      

09:35.808 --> 09:37.810
       - Since she learned      
       what I do for work,      

09:37.877 --> 09:39.478
      she just frets about      
          my lifestyle.         

09:39.545 --> 09:41.948
      So I stopped going.       
- Well, you don't have a fever. 

09:42.014 --> 09:43.749
  Your white blood cell count   
          is normal,            

09:43.816 --> 09:46.052
  so I'm gonna rule out sepsis, 
 but you do have some swelling. 

09:46.118 --> 09:48.554
 So has there been any changes  
      to diet, exercise,        

09:48.621 --> 09:50.423
   sudden weight gain, loss,    
      that kind of thing?       

09:50.489 --> 09:52.692
       - Foods, the usual.      
    Some healthy, some crap.    

09:52.758 --> 09:54.694
      I make it to the gym      
        when I can. Why?        

09:54.760 --> 09:57.997
     - The way I see it is,     
we can dodge the endless backlog

09:58.064 --> 10:00.399
      at imaging by gaming      
         this ourselves.        

10:00.466 --> 10:02.468
 You know, taking a little time 
now and getting a wider picture.

10:02.535 --> 10:06.272
     And then I can schedule    
 appointments for any follow-up 
      tests you might need.     

10:07.473 --> 10:09.208
        (sirens wailing)        

10:09.275 --> 10:11.477
      - 32-year-old male        
    T-boned in his vehicle.     

10:11.544 --> 10:13.212
    GCS 13, BP 100 over 80.     

10:13.279 --> 10:16.015
      Left quadrant injury      
   and a nicked carotid being   
     held together by, uh...    

10:16.082 --> 10:18.084
 - A penny. Don't worry, Beau,  
      I won't let you go.       

10:18.150 --> 10:20.019
 - We were just down the street 
   from here when it happened.  

10:20.086 --> 10:22.021
 We tried trading off with her, 
     but she didn't want to.    

10:22.088 --> 10:23.723
     - Were you in the car,     
           too, Penny?          

10:23.789 --> 10:25.424
         - I'm the idiot        
       who drove into him.      

10:25.491 --> 10:27.059
     His door was smashed,      
        so I crawled in         

10:27.126 --> 10:29.862
and saw his neck pumping blood. 
My instincts said that was bad. 

10:29.929 --> 10:31.864
        - Good instinct.        
   Any loss of consciousness?   

10:31.931 --> 10:35.401
  - I was fading until she said 
that thing about stealing a car.

10:35.468 --> 10:37.103
    - Dude, cone of silence.    

10:37.169 --> 10:38.904
        - Sorry, sorry.         
- Did you two know each before? 

10:38.971 --> 10:42.708
    - No, but shared trauma     
 forces you to get close fast.  

10:42.775 --> 10:44.410
         - Monitor's up.        
  - Claire, make sure vascular  

10:44.477 --> 10:46.712
   knows it's an open carotid.  
  Bash, why aren't we clamped?  

10:46.779 --> 10:48.180
      - Penny, I'll switch      
         spots with you.        

10:48.247 --> 10:49.882
   - Does it have to be now?    

10:50.916 --> 10:52.918
     - I think I just found     
    the source of the bleed.    

10:52.985 --> 10:54.987
     Skin's swelling, too.      
       You see the rash?        

10:55.054 --> 10:56.856
- What kind of reaction is that?
         - I don't know.        

10:56.922 --> 10:59.091
     - Penny, are you ready?    
   - No, no. What if I let go   

10:59.158 --> 11:00.359
 too early or it doesn't work?  

11:00.426 --> 11:02.228
         - Vascular says        
     we have to go to them.     

11:02.294 --> 11:03.562
      They're better set up     
    to handle this upstairs.    

11:03.629 --> 11:05.131
          - Fine. Bash,         
     why aren't we clamped?     

11:05.197 --> 11:07.166
  - Because of me, okay? This   
 whole thing is because of me.  

11:07.233 --> 11:09.068
  - I'm sure that's not true.   
         - Yes, it is.          

11:09.135 --> 11:10.403
 I work at a car rental place,  

11:10.469 --> 11:11.737
          and every day         
      just feels so empty.      

11:11.804 --> 11:13.372
     And today, I just had      
     a compulsion to run,       

11:13.439 --> 11:15.508
 so I borrowed a set of keys--  
            - Okay.             

11:15.574 --> 11:17.109
   We'll count down together,   
      I'll take your place,     

11:17.176 --> 11:19.211
     but it has to be now!      
       (monitor beeping)        

11:19.278 --> 11:21.480
      (breathing heavily)       
     - I trust you, Penny.      

11:21.547 --> 11:23.749
         - Okay, one...         
       - Okay, one, two...      

11:23.816 --> 11:25.918
        - Two. Three...         

11:26.686 --> 11:28.087
           Thank you.           

11:29.922 --> 11:32.258
         (tense music)          

11:35.327 --> 11:37.763
   Got it. Great job, Penny.    

11:37.830 --> 11:40.032
        - EP's dropping.        
    - June, forget vascular.    

11:40.099 --> 11:41.701
       We can take care of      
      the abdo bleed here.      

11:41.767 --> 11:43.402
 - What? No. It's way too risky 
        with the carotid.       

11:43.469 --> 11:45.671
 - It's too risky to wait. He's 
  lost too much blood already.  

11:45.738 --> 11:47.339
   - It's my call, alright?     
  Just stay on blood products   

11:47.406 --> 11:48.641
     and get him stabilized     
         for transport.         

11:48.708 --> 11:50.409
       I'll go coordinate       
         with vascular.         

11:50.476 --> 11:52.011
       (monitor beeping)        

11:55.114 --> 11:58.084
   - You said you trusted me.   

11:58.150 --> 12:00.953
              Why?              
 - You stayed, I would've left. 

12:01.020 --> 12:05.591
    - Except you would have     
    been so much better off     
     if you never met me.       

12:07.359 --> 12:09.228
     (Mags): Are you okay?      

12:11.897 --> 12:13.466
             (thump)            
           (coughing)           

12:14.300 --> 12:15.401
    So you saved the others?    

12:15.468 --> 12:16.635
        (muffled speech)        

12:17.169 --> 12:18.838
   (Bashir): I know you told    
      that police officer       

12:18.904 --> 12:20.473
       that you'd get him       
        after we finish.        

12:20.539 --> 12:22.975
       But what if instead      
       of that, you don't.      

12:23.743 --> 12:25.211
        (muffled thump)         

12:25.277 --> 12:27.480
           (beeping)            

12:28.447 --> 12:29.715
   He's lost too much blood.    

12:29.782 --> 12:31.751
 His body is rejecting whatever 
      metal is inside him.      

12:31.817 --> 12:34.253
      - We got you, Bash.       
  Just tell us what you need.   

12:34.887 --> 12:36.155
          - Get him...          
          (indistinct)          

12:36.222 --> 12:37.823
       (monitors beeping)       

12:39.258 --> 12:40.259
            - Theo.             

12:40.693 --> 12:43.062
      I wanted you to know      
      that Mrs. Sampson...      

12:43.129 --> 12:45.164
    - Rheumatoid arthritis,     
   needs to adjust her meds.    

12:45.231 --> 12:49.235
   - I was doing my paperwork   
      and noticed a flag on     
       yesterday's X-rays.      

12:49.301 --> 12:51.170
  I had the senior radiologist  
          take a look.          

12:51.237 --> 12:53.572
     It's actually a stress     
     fracture in her femur.     

12:54.240 --> 12:55.541
       She'll need a pin.       

12:55.608 --> 12:57.710
   - Were you double-checking   
            my work?            

12:57.777 --> 13:00.746
   - No, just navigating the    
 bureaucracy, which is my job.  

13:00.813 --> 13:03.849
   They've already slotted her  
 for surgery, so it's all good. 

13:09.054 --> 13:12.324
    You know how easy stress    
     fractures are to miss.     

13:12.892 --> 13:17.563
   And Daphne was impressed     
and touched by how holistically 
     you took everything.       

13:17.630 --> 13:19.131
Nobody else would do that here. 

13:19.198 --> 13:22.001
       - I don't need you       
     to make me feel better     
    about missing something.    

13:22.067 --> 13:23.836
        (coffee pouring)        

13:25.237 --> 13:28.207
 - Why don't you let me come to 
 the funeral with you tomorrow? 

13:28.774 --> 13:31.143
    - Bash said the family      
    wants to keep it small.     

13:31.210 --> 13:34.480
      - I know, but Theo--      
 - I don't want you there, Liz. 

13:35.648 --> 13:39.418
  Can we not make it about us   
  in this particular moment?    

13:39.485 --> 13:42.922
- I'm trying to talk about you. 
     About what you need.       

13:42.988 --> 13:44.824
     Why would you not want     
         support there?         

13:44.890 --> 13:47.526
         - You tell me.         
   'Cause you clearly already   
        have the answer.        

13:47.593 --> 13:49.762
       - I just know that       
      you're resisting us.      

13:49.829 --> 13:52.565
   Getting to know my family,   
     letting me know yours.     

13:52.631 --> 13:55.034
          And it hurts.         
    You're a good man, Theo.    

13:55.100 --> 13:57.870
     I want those things.       
 Do you not want them with me?  

13:57.937 --> 13:59.071
        - I don't know.         

13:59.538 --> 14:01.941
        I have lost sight       
       of all of it, Liz.       

14:02.007 --> 14:03.642
          Of myself...          

14:06.011 --> 14:08.747
- I can't keep waiting for you. 

14:13.652 --> 14:16.188
    - What the hell is this?    
 - We had to stop the bleeding. 

14:16.255 --> 14:19.024
 Good thing, too, the shrapnel  
     ruptured the spleen.       

14:19.091 --> 14:22.294
 - So you took his spleen out   
even though I told you to wait. 

14:22.361 --> 14:23.896
           (scoffs)             

14:26.265 --> 14:28.701
   But there was another one    
   just like this in the...     

14:30.035 --> 14:32.371
     - Please, tell me there    
    was no baby in that car.    

14:32.438 --> 14:35.741
   - There wasn't because Beau  
  drove off and left her here.  

14:35.808 --> 14:38.210
       (monitor beeping)        

14:41.614 --> 14:43.449
    (distant traffic noise)     

14:43.515 --> 14:46.018
   - Look for her badge I.D.    

14:46.085 --> 14:49.221
    Anything else in there.     
       Her stethoscope.         

14:49.288 --> 14:50.923
        - Are you sure?         

14:50.990 --> 14:52.691
     I mean, this can wait      
        if you're not--         

14:52.758 --> 14:55.527
  - Yes, her family will want   
    whatever you can find.      

14:55.594 --> 14:57.062
            Thanks.             

14:57.129 --> 14:58.764
         - Uh, Bash...          

14:59.598 --> 15:02.701
       Um, the last times       
     I spoke to her were...     

15:02.768 --> 15:04.570
      - Yeah, she told me.      

15:05.437 --> 15:06.805
           - I was...           

15:07.873 --> 15:09.909
       I didn't mean to--       
            - Claire.           

15:09.975 --> 15:11.810
        I don't know what       
       you want me to say.      

15:14.413 --> 15:15.781
 - You don't understand, okay?  

15:15.848 --> 15:18.384
   I didn't even know that she  
 existed until a few weeks ago. 

15:18.450 --> 15:20.452
     Okay? Her mother just      
   dropped her off and left.    

15:20.519 --> 15:22.621
    - So you decided to just    
        pay that forward?       

15:22.688 --> 15:24.757
       - No, I don't know       
        how to bed a dad.       

15:24.823 --> 15:26.926
     Or anything, really...     

15:26.992 --> 15:29.094
       - So you sack up         
       and ask for help.        

15:29.161 --> 15:31.196
Call a friend, family, anything.

15:31.263 --> 15:33.666
     - I don't really have      
         any of that.           

15:33.732 --> 15:36.368
         And when I try,        
       the words, they...       

15:36.435 --> 15:38.537
         - Okay, fine.          
  But you could've handed her   

15:38.604 --> 15:41.173
    to one of the hundreds      
    of staff who work here.     

15:41.240 --> 15:42.908
         And instead,           
     you just ditched her.      

15:42.975 --> 15:45.144
     Do you know what that      
       could do to her?         

15:45.210 --> 15:47.279
Or how many people want babies? 
            - June!             

15:47.346 --> 15:49.348
      - Look, I know that       
  I'm a piece of trash, okay?   

15:49.415 --> 15:50.683
  I don't need to be reminded.  

15:50.749 --> 15:51.951
       - Actually, yeah,        
        I think you do!         

15:52.017 --> 15:52.985
            - June!             
            - What?             

15:53.052 --> 15:54.753
      - May I speak to you      
          for a moment?         

15:57.656 --> 15:58.624
       What are you doing?      

15:58.691 --> 15:59.959
       - He needs to be         
       held accountable.        

16:00.025 --> 16:02.161
       - But not by you.        
 The social worker called CAS.  

16:02.227 --> 16:03.862
       - What's going on?       

16:03.929 --> 16:05.297
  - Penny, you're still here?   

16:05.364 --> 16:07.566
- Yeah, I mean, he's so anxious,
      and he needs someone.     

16:07.633 --> 16:09.601
       And it's my fault        
       he's here, right?        

16:09.668 --> 16:12.604
        A nurse told him        
       that he's having...      

16:12.671 --> 16:14.173
   portal-thrombo something.    

16:14.239 --> 16:16.208
     Can one of you explain     
  because we don't understand?  

16:16.275 --> 16:19.211
    - Portal vein thrombosis    
     is when there's a clot     

16:19.278 --> 16:22.915
 in his portal vein that blocks 
    blood flow to his liver.    

16:22.982 --> 16:25.884
    - But can't that kill you   
  if your liver stops working?  

16:25.951 --> 16:27.353
         - We're keeping        
       a close eye on him.      

16:27.419 --> 16:29.488
   And for now, he's stable.    
          - And Amy?            

16:30.122 --> 16:32.257
       His baby, he said        
       that's her name.         

16:32.324 --> 16:34.593
      - The social worker       
   looped in children's aid.    

16:34.660 --> 16:36.195
        - We're required        
       to call the police.      

16:36.261 --> 16:37.830
  - Are they gonna arrest him?  

16:37.896 --> 16:39.298
          Oh, my God.           

16:39.365 --> 16:41.033
       I was trying to fix      
        my own dumb life,       

16:41.100 --> 16:43.836
   and instead, I just like,    
        destroyed his.          

16:44.436 --> 16:45.738
         (Penny sighs)          

16:46.772 --> 16:48.574
  - Does Beau have PVT or not?  

16:48.640 --> 16:50.509
    - We have him on heparin    
     to try help manage it.     

16:50.576 --> 16:52.311
    You know, she's out here    
blaming herself for all of this.

16:52.378 --> 16:54.413
  Meanwhile, you're the one who 
jumped in and cut out his spleen

16:54.480 --> 16:56.015
  which is probably the reason  
         that the clot--        

16:56.081 --> 16:57.349
        - He was dying.         
         He needed it.          

16:57.416 --> 16:58.617
     I know you know that.      
          - No, you.            

16:58.684 --> 17:00.753
    Okay, I know you, Bash.     
     And you needed this.       

17:00.819 --> 17:02.988
      But with everything       
  that's going on, you needed   
       an escape hatch.         

17:03.055 --> 17:05.357
 - You are no better, alright?  
  You are pissed off at Beau    

17:05.424 --> 17:07.459
     for not asking for help    
   when you have said nothing   

17:07.526 --> 17:09.328
       since I called you       
         three days ago.        

17:10.896 --> 17:12.231
        I'm on no sleep.        

17:12.865 --> 17:14.500
       And these thoughts       
       and memories of her      

17:14.566 --> 17:15.801
are just flooding into my head, 

17:15.868 --> 17:17.069
 all at once and out of order,  

17:17.136 --> 17:18.270
       and they're messing      
        with my reality.        

17:18.337 --> 17:20.339
      And yeah, maybe Beau      
        was a distraction       

17:20.406 --> 17:22.508
        that I needed--         
          - Stop it!            

17:24.443 --> 17:26.845
        I can't do this.        

17:29.782 --> 17:32.618
       Okay, I wish that        
     I could, but I can't.      

17:46.098 --> 17:48.600
       - I haven't been         
     to church in so long.      

17:49.134 --> 17:51.537
       I mean, we aren't        
       Catholic, but...         

17:51.603 --> 17:53.939
       I remember my dad,       

17:54.006 --> 17:57.743
      the way he would help     
  his congregation meet grief,  

17:57.810 --> 18:00.746
he could just hold it with him. 

18:02.147 --> 18:04.483
    He quit being a pastor,     
     did I tell you that?       

18:04.550 --> 18:06.285
       - No, is he okay?        

18:06.919 --> 18:08.487
        - I don't know.         

18:09.021 --> 18:10.522
           I hope so.           

18:16.128 --> 18:18.464
      (indistinct chatter)      

18:26.638 --> 18:28.240
     - Um, it's her sister.     

18:28.307 --> 18:30.676
     - Looked like she was      
       waving you over.         

18:30.742 --> 18:33.011
       - I think she was        
        just saying hi.         

18:33.745 --> 18:35.414
- Have you talked to the family 

18:35.481 --> 18:36.949
          about where           
     they want you to sit?      

18:37.015 --> 18:38.884
    - No, was I supposed to?    

18:38.951 --> 18:42.054
   - Sometimes, they reserve    
 specific rows for loved ones.  

18:42.121 --> 18:44.523
     - Let's just give them     
           some space.          

18:44.590 --> 18:46.992
     - Sure. Tell me where      
     you want to be then.       

18:48.861 --> 18:50.629
      (indistinct chatter)      

19:02.074 --> 19:04.643
     Do you see anyone else     
         here you know?         

19:08.747 --> 19:10.349
         - I know him.          

19:11.783 --> 19:14.219
        (dramatic music)        

19:27.266 --> 19:29.034
          - Hi, June.           

19:29.868 --> 19:34.173
       - Hi, Dr. Bishop.        
        Uh, hi, Claire.         

19:34.840 --> 19:36.341
       I think she, uh...       

19:36.408 --> 19:39.811
  It would mean a lot to her    
  to know that you were here.   

19:39.878 --> 19:41.547
          Both of you.          

19:43.382 --> 19:44.950
          I should...           

20:06.505 --> 20:08.540
       - How have you been      
      keeping, Dr. Bishop?      

20:08.607 --> 20:10.275
    - I've been well, Theo.     
        I've been well.         

20:10.342 --> 20:13.278
     - When our fourth-year     
   med students cycle through   

20:13.345 --> 20:15.314
 and see your name on the wall  
    outside the Trauma OR,      

20:15.380 --> 20:17.149
      they often tell us        
     you're their teacher.      

20:17.683 --> 20:19.051
        Do you enjoy it?        

20:19.618 --> 20:21.453
       - Well, it depends       
         on the student.        

20:21.920 --> 20:24.756
    If they're burdened with    
     glorious purpose, I do.    

20:25.924 --> 20:30.128
          (in French)           

20:37.035 --> 20:39.871
             - Amen.            
          (all): Amen.          

20:39.938 --> 20:43.575
          (in French)           

21:32.991 --> 21:34.926
     - Who was my Magalie?      

21:34.993 --> 21:37.162
     (high-pitched ringing)     

21:37.229 --> 21:39.731
  (Mags): The scars will fade.  

21:40.766 --> 21:43.235
      I really hated you        
    the first night we met.     

21:43.302 --> 21:44.803
           (chuckles)           

21:44.870 --> 21:46.438
           (crashing)           

21:47.005 --> 21:49.641
   (officer): The restaurant    
       is a crime scene.        

21:50.876 --> 21:53.412
        (dramatic music)        

21:59.451 --> 22:01.687
- Why do you keep running away? 
         Who are you?           

22:05.057 --> 22:08.193
      (indistinct chatter)      

22:23.642 --> 22:26.011
cawing)                         

22:28.580 --> 22:32.384
      (speaking in French)      

22:32.451 --> 22:34.086
           - Sorry?             

22:35.020 --> 22:38.023
 (continues speaking in French) 

22:45.731 --> 22:47.866
    - Oh, you're lost. Um...    

22:48.967 --> 22:51.103
     Okay, are you looking      
     for someone's grave?       

22:51.169 --> 22:54.039
      (speaking in French)      

22:54.439 --> 22:55.841
         - Your father.         

22:56.541 --> 22:57.809
             - Yes.             

23:02.214 --> 23:04.549
       - Madame Leblanc?        
            - Yes.              

23:04.616 --> 23:05.984
       - I'm Jed Bishop.        

23:06.451 --> 23:08.387
       - The Dr. Bishop.        

23:08.453 --> 23:11.590
      She talked about you      
      with such reverence.      

23:11.656 --> 23:14.359
- Your daughter was remarkable. 

23:15.026 --> 23:16.862
       Best of all of us.       

23:16.928 --> 23:18.330
          - Thank you.          

23:20.265 --> 23:22.234
        (dramatic music)        

23:37.349 --> 23:42.721
   - The last time we spoke,    
    you said you'd swapped      
     talk therapy for CBT?      

23:42.788 --> 23:44.456
          (chuckles)            
   - Yeah, I get enough talk    

23:44.523 --> 23:45.791
       in my NA meetings.       

23:46.691 --> 23:48.927
 - It sounds like your chief's  
     been very supportive.      

23:48.994 --> 23:53.031
    - Yeah. She's... a true     
     humanist, which is--       

23:53.098 --> 23:55.167
- Not an easy sell in that job. 

23:57.035 --> 23:59.704
  - Mags was the one who tried  
      the hardest with me.      

23:59.771 --> 24:02.374
And who saw things the clearest.

24:06.044 --> 24:09.347
      She's also the person     
     I was hardest on, Jed.     

24:10.282 --> 24:12.350
    I treated her terribly.     

24:12.417 --> 24:13.685
  - Well, if anyone understood  

24:13.752 --> 24:15.687
   emotion getting the better   
      of you, it was Mags.      

24:15.754 --> 24:18.957
 - It wasn't about the assault  
       or the addiction,        

24:19.024 --> 24:21.526
the way I treated her. It was...

24:22.828 --> 24:25.197
  She had all this potential.   

24:25.263 --> 24:29.000
    Always so excited to get    
     started, and I just...     

24:29.935 --> 24:33.338
 From where I stand, the system 
is broken and it can't be fixed.

24:33.405 --> 24:36.107
And that's not how Mags saw it. 

24:37.075 --> 24:38.977
        I'm angry, Jed.         

24:39.778 --> 24:43.215
    I envied her optimism,      
    and I envied her youth.     

24:45.250 --> 24:46.918
           (sighing)            
    - It's alright, Claire.     

24:46.985 --> 24:48.653
        - No, it's not.         

24:49.387 --> 24:51.790
 - Look who you're talking to.  

24:52.491 --> 24:54.960
    When I had my accident,     
        I lost a step.          

24:55.026 --> 24:58.230
  That anger... I understand.   

25:00.265 --> 25:01.800
           - Yeah...            

25:02.767 --> 25:05.303
   You sound happy, though,     
 when you talk about teaching.  

25:05.370 --> 25:06.505
          - Hmm, I am.          

25:06.571 --> 25:09.174
  But Memorial, my time there,  

25:09.241 --> 25:11.443
       that was the place.      

25:12.177 --> 25:13.712
       That was my time.        

25:14.479 --> 25:18.283
        Nothing will...         
 Nothing else will come close.  

25:21.453 --> 25:24.456
         - Mr. Leblanc?         
        I'm Theo Hunter.        

25:24.523 --> 25:28.026
  I worked with your daughter,  
   she was a... a good friend.  

25:28.093 --> 25:29.561
       - I think you have       
         daughters, too.        

25:29.628 --> 25:31.730
     - Yeah, 9 and 11 now.      

25:31.796 --> 25:33.899
     Oh, they're 10 and 12.     

25:33.965 --> 25:36.468
- I couldn't keep track either. 
       It goes so fast.         

25:36.535 --> 25:40.205
Um, do they know what they want 
    to do with their lives?     

25:40.272 --> 25:42.741
       - Last I checked,        
    one wanted to be a vet,     

25:42.807 --> 25:44.543
  and the other wanted to open  

25:44.609 --> 25:47.879
a donut slash manicure business,
           you know...          

25:50.081 --> 25:54.719
    - I should've told her      
  more how... how proud I am.   

25:55.520 --> 25:58.390
   - She knew, sir. She did.    

26:00.025 --> 26:04.296
    - Must be hard the hours    
       your job requires.       

26:04.863 --> 26:06.831
 The time away can unmoor you.  

26:06.898 --> 26:09.734
     - And yeah, my kids,       
  they mostly live in Sudbury   

26:09.801 --> 26:11.870
       with their mother        
        because I, uh--         

26:11.937 --> 26:15.507
     - Found your purpose       
  in that crazy busy hospital   

26:15.574 --> 26:18.577
   like my daughter did. Hmm?   

26:18.643 --> 26:20.812
      (indistinct chatter)      

26:31.089 --> 26:32.657
             - Hi.              

26:34.492 --> 26:37.195
        - Hello, Bashir.        
          - Hey, um...          

26:37.729 --> 26:40.765
   I just wanted to tell you    
        how sorry I am.         

26:41.633 --> 26:43.168
             Um...              

26:43.735 --> 26:48.139
  Mags, she saw me, and, uh...  
        it was this thing       

26:48.206 --> 26:50.709
  that we always used to say.   
      - I'm sorry, what?        

26:50.775 --> 26:53.645
   - The question you asked     
   about which Mags we knew.    

26:53.712 --> 26:57.849
I've been thinking of a memory, 
but... it's more of a feeling.  

26:57.916 --> 27:00.518
   - Why didn't you call us?    

27:02.654 --> 27:04.089
            - Uh...             

27:04.623 --> 27:07.626
  That night, Mags didn't want  
         to bother you.         

27:07.692 --> 27:10.695
      We knew that you and      
   Mr. Leblanc were in Italy,   

27:10.762 --> 27:12.697
     and there was nothing      
      you could've done.        

27:12.764 --> 27:14.733
       - I would've wanted      
         to talk to her.        

27:14.799 --> 27:16.701
   - When she was intubated,    

27:16.768 --> 27:19.371
   we had... we didn't think    
     it would go this way.      

27:19.437 --> 27:21.373
           - It wasn't          
     your decision to make.     

27:23.241 --> 27:26.378
      - I didn't, she did.      
     - Why was she working?     

27:26.444 --> 27:29.180
 If she was sick, she was sick. 

27:29.247 --> 27:31.583
   You should've stopped her.   

27:31.650 --> 27:33.485
   - Mrs. Leblanc, I'm Theo.    

27:33.551 --> 27:35.820
  I'm so sorry for your loss.   

27:35.887 --> 27:37.989
        (dramatic music)        

27:41.126 --> 27:44.195
      She's just in pain.       
  She doesn't know you, Bash.   

27:44.262 --> 27:47.565
     Let's go get some air.     
     - Stop trying to help.     

27:54.372 --> 27:56.908
cooing)                         

27:58.576 --> 28:01.146
    (distant sirens wailing)    

28:18.430 --> 28:22.000
     (church bells ringing      
       in the distance)         

28:30.375 --> 28:32.944
         (gentle music)         

28:40.685 --> 28:42.787
 (phone ringing and vibrating)  

28:42.854 --> 28:44.856
      (indistinct chatter)      

28:44.923 --> 28:46.257
             Hello?             

28:46.324 --> 28:49.227
    - Dr. Hamed, it's Penny,    
        the car stealer.        

28:49.294 --> 28:50.962
 - How did you get this number? 

28:51.029 --> 28:52.263
      - Internet. Listen--      

28:52.330 --> 28:54.165
       - Uh, are you still      
        at the hospital?        

28:54.232 --> 28:56.301
     - Look, Beau is worse,     
           physically.          

28:56.367 --> 28:57.869
             - Okay.            
    What do his doctors say?    

28:57.936 --> 29:00.071
- Well, that it's under control,
           but I mean,          

29:00.138 --> 29:02.440
         he's in pain           
       and tastes blood.        

29:02.507 --> 29:04.175
  And since variceal bleeding   

29:04.242 --> 29:06.077
   can mean worsening portal    
      vein thrombosis...        

29:06.144 --> 29:08.079
  - How do you know all this?   
       - Dude, internet.        

29:08.146 --> 29:10.882
 Anyway, they just keep saying  
     concerning variables,      

29:10.949 --> 29:13.384
    and how we need to wait     
        and see, but...         

29:13.451 --> 29:15.120
     since you're the guy       
  who scooped out his spleen,   

29:15.186 --> 29:16.821
       I was hoping you'd       
         do something--         

29:16.888 --> 29:19.491
    - I'm not there anymore,    
      and I'm sure his team     
        is on top of it.        

29:19.557 --> 29:21.392
    - Yeah, but except Beau     
       says he's dying.         

29:21.459 --> 29:22.761
           And look,            
    I can't prove anything,     

29:22.827 --> 29:25.029
      but we both just have     
     this terrible feeling.     

29:25.096 --> 29:26.765
         Beau needs me,         
       I'll call you back.      

29:26.831 --> 29:28.833
      (indistinct chatter)      

29:32.604 --> 29:35.740
 - Hey, uh, Penny just called.  
    Beau's in rough shape.      

29:35.807 --> 29:37.008
         - I'm sure that        
       if his vitals drop       

29:37.075 --> 29:38.810
      and they have to do       
     something, they will.      

29:38.877 --> 29:41.112
 - Yeah, except they both think 
it's worse than anyone realizes,

29:41.179 --> 29:43.248
 and they want us to intervene. 
    - Bash, I can't just call   

29:43.314 --> 29:44.749
       and say the patient      
      is having a feeling.      

29:44.816 --> 29:47.085
 No one's gonna listen to that. 
   - Well, maybe they should.   

29:48.653 --> 29:49.988
            Mags...             

29:50.054 --> 29:53.858
    She knew what she felt.     
 She knew before the data did.  

29:58.530 --> 30:00.131
       What are you doing?      

30:00.765 --> 30:02.267
- Calling the one person I know 

30:02.333 --> 30:04.135
  will hijack another person's  
     patient to do something    

30:04.202 --> 30:06.905
 potentially stupid on the off  
     chance that it helps.      

30:06.971 --> 30:08.740
        (phone ringing)         

30:10.742 --> 30:12.076
          - Yeah, hi?           

30:12.143 --> 30:14.579
    - Look, I have a patient    
  with portal vein thrombosis.  

30:14.646 --> 30:15.980
 The staff surgeon's ignoring,  

30:16.047 --> 30:17.882
    and we need to get blood    
      flowing to his liver.     

30:17.949 --> 30:19.450
     - Sorry, who is this?      
         - Oh, my God.          

30:19.517 --> 30:22.420
There's no time for us to listen
  to you amuse yourself, Mark.  

30:22.487 --> 30:24.022
             - Us?              

30:24.088 --> 30:25.490
        - Hi, Dr. Novak.        

30:25.557 --> 30:26.991
             - Hi!              

30:27.058 --> 30:28.493
     If your patient truly      
         needed this,           

30:28.560 --> 30:29.861
  wouldn't vascular be on it?   

30:29.928 --> 30:32.330
   - Well, they won't because   
      after a car accident,     

30:32.397 --> 30:35.099
    he reacted to the metal     
    lodged in his abdomen.      

30:35.166 --> 30:37.268
    And you can't do a shunt    
        without a stint.        

30:37.735 --> 30:38.837
       - It's reasonable.       

30:38.903 --> 30:40.738
        - But he also has       
     a rotated portal vein.     

30:40.805 --> 30:44.209
 So they probably decided that, 
    you know, it's gonna make   
     placement challenging.     

30:44.776 --> 30:48.079
   - Cowards. Still, I'm not    
     hearing a big reason       

30:48.146 --> 30:49.514
 why we need to rush into this. 

30:49.581 --> 30:52.283
     - He's got a sense of      
impending doom we can't ignore. 

30:52.350 --> 30:54.285
      - Listen, you need        
 to shut up and do this. Okay?  

30:54.352 --> 30:57.055
       - Since when do you      
     let someone's feelings     
      dictate your actions?     

30:57.121 --> 30:59.157
       You know this guy?       
              - No.             

30:59.224 --> 31:01.893
And, you know, he's actually... 
     He's a piece of work.      

31:01.960 --> 31:05.363
     You know, he abandoned     
  his daughter at the hospital  
     like she meant nothing.    

31:05.430 --> 31:07.532
     And then this woman,       
   she accidentally hits him    

31:07.599 --> 31:10.602
  with her car because she's    
running away from her own crap. 

31:10.668 --> 31:12.904
       And now she's there      
        fighting for him,       

31:12.971 --> 31:14.305
           even though          
     he doesn't deserve it.     

31:14.372 --> 31:16.708
   Look, I need to just help    
     these people, and...       

31:16.774 --> 31:18.843
            (sighs)             
            Please.             

31:19.277 --> 31:22.647
  - Any thoughts on how to get  
   around using a metal stent?  

31:22.714 --> 31:24.249
           - Not yet.           

31:31.089 --> 31:34.092
- I thought Novak couldn't have 
 Trauma OR privileges anymore.  

31:34.158 --> 31:35.960
       - Yeah, well, I do.      
       And if I leave now,      

31:36.027 --> 31:37.896
    I can be there in like,     
       two hours. So...         

31:37.962 --> 31:39.497
       - You're leaving?        

31:39.564 --> 31:41.766
   - I couldn't even make it    
     through her service.       

31:42.901 --> 31:44.369
  - Are you going to be okay?   

31:45.270 --> 31:46.604
           - Are you?           

31:47.138 --> 31:49.407
   Because I remember the day   
       of her transplant,       

31:49.474 --> 31:51.542
        you said that if        
       she didn't make it,      

31:52.610 --> 31:54.646
      you wouldn't either.      

31:59.417 --> 32:02.020
          (soft music)          

32:17.535 --> 32:20.171
     - It's okay, habibti,      
         go to sleep.           

32:20.238 --> 32:22.740
              (♪♪)              

32:41.693 --> 32:43.094
        - Are you okay?         

32:44.629 --> 32:46.531
         Is she asleep?         

32:49.968 --> 32:52.470
   Can I ask you a question?    
            - Sure.             

32:52.537 --> 32:55.106
  - Why didn't you just tell    
the truth about being a doctor? 

32:55.173 --> 32:56.841
      If you had said that      
       from the beginning,      

32:56.908 --> 32:59.077
      wouldn't all of this      
       have been avoided?       

32:59.143 --> 33:01.646
    - We could get deported.    

33:01.713 --> 33:04.349
      I was a doctor once,      
        I'm not anymore.        

33:08.252 --> 33:10.355
    - The thing is I kind of    
     told the truth for you.    

33:10.421 --> 33:13.758
  Everyone knows what you did   
  and how you saved everyone.   

33:14.325 --> 33:16.861
  But before you say anything,  

33:16.928 --> 33:21.799
  maybe just, maybe... things   
      will work out fine.       

33:24.235 --> 33:26.571
              (♪♪)              

33:36.647 --> 33:38.583
        So can't go off         
    the shelf for this one.     

33:38.649 --> 33:41.786
      - The 3D printer uses     
     biodegradable polymer,     

33:41.853 --> 33:43.821
     but I've never printed     
        a vascular stent.       

33:43.888 --> 33:46.124
      - It could, though.       
 I mean, I read a study on it.  

33:46.190 --> 33:49.927
    Yes, I do read studies.     
     Piss off, both of ya.      

33:49.994 --> 33:51.696
- I asked the tech to stay late.

33:51.763 --> 33:54.165
   She'll need CT imaging so    
  the software can customize.   

33:54.232 --> 33:57.335
      - Yeah, I can do that     
     while June informs and     
      consents our patient.     

33:57.402 --> 34:00.772
  - Dr. Curtis, this was all at 
 your behest, are we on or not? 

34:00.838 --> 34:04.575
- When did we get a 3D printer? 
        - "We" didn't.          

34:04.642 --> 34:06.277
         A few surgeons         
       pooled grant money.      

34:06.344 --> 34:08.813
        I use it to make        
      custom ostomy seals.      

34:08.880 --> 34:10.481
     - Won't see that kind      
     of socialized effort       

34:10.548 --> 34:12.150
when you go to Cleveland, June. 

34:12.216 --> 34:13.951
        (Singh chuckles)        
             - Word.            

34:20.858 --> 34:22.827
             - Hi.              
       - Before you yell        

34:22.894 --> 34:24.429
    at him again, I checked.    

34:24.495 --> 34:26.831
     And they said he could     
     visit Amy for an hour.     

34:26.898 --> 34:28.900
    The social worker's down    
        the hall waiting.       

34:28.966 --> 34:31.069
    - They have her placed      
  with a family nearby. So...   

34:31.135 --> 34:35.473
     - He felt so bad about     
     what he did, I thought     
     seeing her might help.     

34:36.374 --> 34:37.909
             - And?             

34:39.043 --> 34:40.311
            Has it?             

34:43.915 --> 34:47.185
 - So is this 3D-printed valve  
  thing really gonna happen?    

34:47.251 --> 34:49.921
 - If you consent, we'll divert 
     blood around your clot.    

34:49.987 --> 34:51.522
   You need to realize that,    

34:51.589 --> 34:54.092
you know, although this medical 
 technology has been approved,  

34:54.158 --> 34:56.561
        it is still new.        
     So there are variables     

34:56.627 --> 34:58.496
     and not every outcome      
       has been studied.        

34:58.563 --> 35:00.731
- In other words, no guarantees.

35:00.798 --> 35:02.800
       - There never are.       

35:05.736 --> 35:08.072
       - Why did you leave      
         your daughter?         

35:10.475 --> 35:11.809
         - I'm scared.          

35:12.877 --> 35:15.413
  I don't know how to love her  
         the right way.         

35:15.480 --> 35:16.881
         (baby cooing)          

35:16.948 --> 35:19.650
   Look, I know you did a lot   
      to make this happen.      

35:20.518 --> 35:22.220
       I don't really know      
          what to say.          

35:22.286 --> 35:24.522
   - That you'll keep trying.   

35:27.391 --> 35:29.127
          (soft music)          

35:33.498 --> 35:35.133
       - You didn't have        
       to wait up, Dad.         

35:35.666 --> 35:37.135
       - Of course I did.       

35:37.735 --> 35:39.470
       - The girls okay?        

35:39.537 --> 35:41.372
       - Yeah, I'd say so.      

35:41.439 --> 35:43.407
       We watched a movie       
         and walked out         

35:43.474 --> 35:46.777
  for some late night French    
 fries, and then they flopped.  

35:50.748 --> 35:52.216
          How was it?           

35:54.785 --> 35:57.822
      - It's been a tough       
     couple of years, Dad.      

36:00.658 --> 36:03.127
  - Yeah, I know it has, Theo.  

36:05.263 --> 36:07.398
     - Your own job, um...      

36:10.034 --> 36:12.737
  Do you ever worry you just    
  blew it all up for nothing?   

36:12.803 --> 36:13.905
             - No.              

36:14.405 --> 36:16.641
No, I have faith in the journey.

36:18.009 --> 36:19.577
        For both of us.         

36:21.379 --> 36:26.317
    Which is perhaps easier     
    from my vantage point.      

36:30.087 --> 36:32.256
- I'm in the wrong place again. 

36:35.393 --> 36:37.862
I've been fighting against it...

36:40.598 --> 36:42.400
 I'm in the wrong place again.  

36:42.466 --> 36:45.203
            - Hey...            
          (Theo cries)          

36:51.008 --> 36:52.610
        (dramatic music)        

37:03.988 --> 37:05.990
   - Did you know I was here?   

37:06.057 --> 37:09.560
 - Well, it's not far from the  
 church so I'd take a chance.   

37:10.528 --> 37:11.729
  - How long are you in town?   

37:11.796 --> 37:13.931
     - Planning on driving      
         back tonight.          

37:15.800 --> 37:18.302
  - It would have meant a lot   
   to her to know you came.     

37:19.237 --> 37:21.572
 - You know, I think June said  
    exactly the same thing.     

37:21.639 --> 37:24.108
      - Because it's true.      
          We miss you.          

37:25.243 --> 37:28.946
   - Look, the reason I was     
 looking for you is because...  

37:30.748 --> 37:32.850
            (sighs)             
           Bashir...            

37:33.417 --> 37:39.090
        I'm not very good       
     at this either, but...     
      don't blame yourself.     

37:39.590 --> 37:41.058
 - Why are you telling me that? 

37:41.125 --> 37:44.595
  - Remember after my stroke,   
you told me about your parents. 

37:45.229 --> 37:48.299
   How you went there to save   
    them when the bombs came.   

37:49.267 --> 37:51.435
  - I thought you were asleep   
       when I said that.        

37:53.671 --> 37:56.741
     Everyone I care about      
     gets hurt, even you.       

37:56.807 --> 37:58.409
       - We're never gonna      
         agree on this.         

37:58.476 --> 38:00.378
I am only alive because of you. 

38:00.444 --> 38:03.848
    - Your career ended over    
 my medical school transcripts. 

38:03.914 --> 38:06.317
    You lied to protect me.     
    We both know you never      
       spoke to my dean.        

38:06.384 --> 38:08.452
    - I didn't need to speak    
  to him, I knew they existed.  

38:08.519 --> 38:09.720
         - Look, she...         

38:10.087 --> 38:14.091
 When I had first met her, I... 
         I was... I'd...        

38:14.725 --> 38:17.361
       - Spent long enough      
          being ignored         

38:17.428 --> 38:19.764
      by the likes of me        
   that you'd given up hope.    

38:20.531 --> 38:23.000
 - She was the one who saw me.  

38:23.067 --> 38:25.736
  And if I had just been able   
    to walk away that day,      

38:25.803 --> 38:29.040
    if that truck had never     
  started all of this, then--   

38:29.106 --> 38:31.575
    - What? Are you gonna say   
   that she'd still be alive?   

38:31.642 --> 38:33.444
 - Look, I didn't deserve her.  

38:34.178 --> 38:36.681
  Okay, I didn't deserve her.   

38:38.416 --> 38:40.117
   - That's not true, Bashir.   

38:40.184 --> 38:42.987
     It's simply not true.      

38:51.595 --> 38:54.165
        (dramatic music)        

39:03.140 --> 39:05.976
              (♪♪)              

39:20.891 --> 39:23.661
    (distant sirens wailing)    

39:29.700 --> 39:30.901
         (Bishop sighs)         

39:31.802 --> 39:35.873
      I would ask if work       
  was the right place for you   
     at the moment, but...      

39:36.841 --> 39:39.176
  - Today's my last day here.   

39:44.382 --> 39:46.517
       - You're right that      
she wanted me to know everything

39:46.584 --> 39:48.219
     you'd done that night.     

39:49.253 --> 39:54.759
And we'd both be pretty ticked  
off if you let this derail you. 

39:59.930 --> 40:01.632
 - Did you want to come inside? 

40:01.699 --> 40:03.534
      See the place again.      

40:07.138 --> 40:08.906
        Dr. Bishop, I...        

40:08.973 --> 40:10.474
             - Go.              

40:10.541 --> 40:12.443
          (soft music)          

40:25.723 --> 40:27.458
            - Cool.             

40:30.628 --> 40:32.630
     - Beau's vitals still      
         looking good?          

40:32.696 --> 40:34.131
        - Yeah. Weirdly,        

40:34.198 --> 40:36.167
      I think this worked.      
         (phone ringing)        

40:36.233 --> 40:38.002
- Thing's been ringing non-stop.

40:38.068 --> 40:40.337
       - Yeah, our friends      
    in vascular want a word.    

40:40.404 --> 40:43.174
   - I think you mean former    
     friends in vascular.       

40:43.240 --> 40:46.477
 - Speaking of former friends,  

40:46.544 --> 40:50.080
      yours came to see me      
         the other day.         

40:51.115 --> 40:53.150
Said I was messing up your life 

40:53.217 --> 40:55.553
     because I wasn't happy     
           with mine.           

40:57.488 --> 40:59.256
     - Yeah, she had a way      
        of doing that.          

40:59.323 --> 41:00.724
       That kind of thing.      

41:01.192 --> 41:03.494
        - I'm very sorry        
      for your loss, June.      

41:05.863 --> 41:07.598
     - I really loved her.      

41:08.766 --> 41:10.801
 - Irritatingly, she was right. 

41:10.868 --> 41:13.037
        (June chuckles)         
     I did miss Trauma OR.      

41:13.103 --> 41:14.705
 So I made a deal with the CMO  

41:14.772 --> 41:16.307
         to come back.          
            - What?             

41:16.373 --> 41:17.942
         - Yeah, agreed         
      to make me co-chief.      

41:18.008 --> 41:19.643
   Devi's not gonna be happy    
       about that, but--        

41:19.710 --> 41:20.878
    - How could you do that?    

41:20.945 --> 41:22.780
          (laughing)            
    - I thought you'd be...     

41:22.847 --> 41:26.550
    You were pushing for it.    
     - For both of us, Mark.    

41:26.617 --> 41:29.053
     You know, I've already     
      decided I'm leaving.      

41:29.119 --> 41:32.289
        You know what?          
     Just forget about it.      
     Do whatever you want.      

41:34.358 --> 41:37.127
          (soft music)          

41:59.517 --> 42:01.819
        (dramatic music)        

42:05.122 --> 42:08.158
      (indistinct chatter)      

42:11.095 --> 42:12.963
    - Good morning, Bashir.     

42:13.764 --> 42:15.566
          - Hi. Um...           

42:15.633 --> 42:17.801
          I'm just here         
     to clear up my locker.     

42:17.868 --> 42:19.470
     - What if you didn't?      

42:19.537 --> 42:21.205
       There was one spot.      

42:21.272 --> 42:24.341
        If it wasn't her,       
    it would've gone to you.    

42:24.408 --> 42:28.579
   I know it's a complicated    
         thing to ask.          

42:30.948 --> 42:32.783
  - I don't know what to say.   

42:33.417 --> 42:35.319
 - That you'll think about it.  

42:38.222 --> 42:40.824
              (♪♪)              

42:50.601 --> 42:53.370
        (dramatic music)        

43:22.299 --> 43:25.436
       Subtitles: difuze        
